This Lufthansa Airlines Boeing 737-100, seen here on February 26, 1968, had cigar-shaped Pratt & ... [+] Whitney engines that had a fan diameter of 42.5 inches.
When the 737-100 debuted in 1968, it was designed to be low to the ground to ease boarding by ladder.
On the 737 MAX, which debuted in 2017, the engines were placed higher up on the wings and further forward.
The 737 is the bestselling airliner of all time, with over 10,000 produced.
“From a business standpoint, I don’t think Boeing had much option.”